  1. Combine the two years of data into one data frame. Use the Date variable to create a new column for year, which will serve as an identifier. Change the names of the key variables so that they are easier to refer to in your code.

    # Add a year column from the Date variable
my_2002_data$Year <- format(as.Date(my_2002_data$Date, format = "%m/%d/%Y"), "%Y")
my_2022_data$Year <- format(as.Date(my_2022_data$Date, format = "%m/%d/%Y"), "%Y")

# Combine into one data frame
combined_data <- rbind(my_2002_data, my_2022_data)

# Rename key variables

names(combined_data)[names(combined_data) == "Daily.AQI.Value"] <- "AQI"

  2. Create a basic map (or maps) in either leaflet or ggplot showing the locations of the monitoring sites, using different colors for each year. Summarize the spatial distribution of the sites. Does this distribution change from 2002 to 2022?

    library(dplyr)
library(leaflet)

# Deduplicate by Year + Sites
sites <- combined_data %>%
  filter(!is.na(Latitude), !is.na(Longitude)) %>%
  distinct(Year, Sites, .keep_all = TRUE)

# Color palette by year
pal <- colorFactor(palette = "Set1", domain = combined_data$Year)

leaflet(sites) %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  addCircleMarkers(
    lng = ~Longitude,
    lat = ~Latitude,
    color = ~pal(Year),
    stroke = FALSE,
    fillOpacity = 1,
    radius = 6,
    popup = ~paste0(
      "<b>Site: </b>", Sites, "<br/>",
      "<b>Year: </b>", Year, "<br/>",
      "<b>Lat/Lon: </b>", round(Latitude, 4), ", ", round(Longitude, 4)
    )
  ) %>%
  addLegend("bottomright", pal = pal, values = ~Year, title = "Year")

Description: the distribution clearly changed from 2002 to 2022. There were considerable more monitoring sites in 2022 than 2002 in the state of California which is expected given the higher number of observation during 2022 compared to 2002.

  1. Check for any data issues such as missing or implausible values of PM in the combined dataset. Calculate the proportion of missing/implausible values for each year and report any temporal patterns you see in these observations.
# Define implausible as missing, negative, or unreasonably high (e.g., > 400 Âµg/mÂ³)
quality_check <- combined_data %>%
  mutate(
    invalid_PM = ifelse(is.na(PM) | PM < 0 | PM > 400, 1, 0)
  ) %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarise(
    total_obs = n(),
    invalid_obs = sum(invalid_PM),
    prop_invalid = mean(invalid_PM)
  )

print(quality_check)

Conclusions

  • At the state level: even though 2002 had higher mean PM2.5 concentration than 2022 (16.12 vs 8.4), 2022 data reported the highest concentration of 302.5 compared to 104.3 of 2002.

  • At the county level: I showed the top 5 counties with most PM concentration, and I found that while Kern reached the highest concentration in 2002 with 104.3, Siskiyou did so in 2022 with 302.5.

  • At the city level: within Los Angeles, Azusa had the highest PM2.5 concentration in 2002 while Glendora had the highest in 2022.

    Thus, we can conclude that the mean daily concentration of PM2.5 decreased in CA over the 20 years spanning from 2002 to 2022, but 2022 reported higher maximum concentrations compared to 2002 depending on specific locations.
